sublevels.theory:
Here is the standard C Code to define a Linked List Node:
```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};
```
To literally append a new node to the end of a vast Linked List, you have to "Traverse" (walk) the list.
```c
struct Node *current = head;
while (current->next != NULL) {
    current = current->next;
}
// 'current' is now the last node!
current->next = new_node;
```

When deleting a Node in the middle, you CANNOT just `free()` it immediately! If you do, the chain breaks and the rest of the list is lost. You must carefully re-wire the pointer of the PREVIOUS node to point to the NEXT node, bridging the gap, before you `free` the isolated middle node.
